 Extract Volume Shadow Copies using VShadow & VSCMount
Learning Objectives
By completing this lab, you will:

Understand Volume Shadow Copy (VSC) technology and its forensic applications
Install and configure VShadow and VSCMount tools on Linux
Extract Volume Shadow Copies from Windows disk images
Mount VSCs to recover deleted files and analyze historical data
Perform timeline analysis using shadow copy timestamps
Prerequisites
Basic Linux command-line knowledge
Understanding of file systems and disk imaging concepts
Familiarity with forensic investigation principles
Knowledge of Windows file system structure
Lab Environment
Al Nafi provides Linux-based cloud machines for this lab. Simply click Start Lab to access your dedicated environment. The provided Linux machine is bare metal with no pre-installed tools, so you will install all required tools during the lab exercises.

Task 1: Install Required Tools and Prepare Environment
Subtask 1.1: Update System and Install Dependencies
# Update package repositories
sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y

# Install essential dependencies
sudo apt install -y build-essential git cmake libfuse-dev pkg-config autotools-dev autoconf libtool

# Install additional forensic tools
sudo apt install -y sleuthkit autopsy ewf-tools
Subtask 1.2: Install libvshadow (VShadow functionality)
# Clone libvshadow repository
cd /opt
sudo git clone https://github.com/libyal/libvshadow.git
cd libvshadow

# Build and install libvshadow
sudo ./synclibs.sh
sudo ./autogen.sh
sudo ./configure
sudo make
sudo make install
sudo ldconfig
Subtask 1.3: Install libvslvm for LVM support
# Clone and build libvslvm
cd /opt
sudo git clone https://github.com/libyal/libvslvm.git
cd libvslvm

sudo ./synclibs.sh
sudo ./autogen.sh
sudo ./configure
sudo make
sudo make install
sudo ldconfig
Subtask 1.4: Create Sample Windows Disk Image
# Create working directory
mkdir -p ~/vsc_lab
cd ~/vsc_lab

# Create a sample NTFS image with shadow copies (simulation)
dd if=/dev/zero of=windows_disk.img bs=1M count=500

# Format as NTFS (requires ntfs-3g)
sudo apt install -y ntfs-3g
sudo mkfs.ntfs -F windows_disk.img

# Create mount point and mount image
mkdir -p ~/vsc_lab/mount_point
sudo mount -o loop windows_disk.img ~/vsc_lab/mount_point

# Create sample files and directories
sudo mkdir -p ~/vsc_lab/mount_point/Users/TestUser/Documents
sudo echo "Original document content" | sudo tee ~/vsc_lab/mount_point/Users/TestUser/Documents/important.txt
sudo echo "Sensitive data file" | sudo tee ~/vsc_lab/mount_point/Users/TestUser/Documents/confidential.doc

# Unmount for shadow copy simulation
sudo umount ~/vsc_lab/mount_point
Task 2: Extract Volume Shadow Copies using VShadow
Subtask 2.1: Analyze Disk Image for Shadow Copies
# Use vshadowinfo to examine shadow copies
vshadowinfo ~/vsc_lab/windows_disk.img

# List available shadow copies with detailed information
vshadowinfo -v ~/vsc_lab/windows_disk.img > shadow_analysis.txt
cat shadow_analysis.txt
Subtask 2.2: Extract Shadow Copy Information
# Create output directory for extracted data
mkdir -p ~/vsc_lab/extracted_shadows

# Use vshadowmount to mount shadow copies
mkdir -p ~/vsc_lab/vsc_mount
vshadowmount ~/vsc_lab/windows_disk.img ~/vsc_lab/vsc_mount

# List mounted shadow copies
ls -la ~/vsc_lab/vsc_mount/
Subtask 2.3: Export Specific Shadow Copies
# Export first shadow copy to separate file
vshadowexport -t ~/vsc_lab/extracted_shadows ~/vsc_lab/windows_disk.img

# Verify exported shadow copies
ls -la ~/vsc_lab/extracted_shadows/
Task 3: Mount VSCs and Recover Deleted Files
Subtask 3.1: Mount Individual Shadow Copies
# Create mount points for each shadow copy
mkdir -p ~/vsc_lab/shadow_mounts/vsc1
mkdir -p ~/vsc_lab/shadow_mounts/vsc2

# Mount first shadow copy (if available)
if [ -f ~/vsc_lab/extracted_shadows/vsc1 ]; then
    sudo mount -o loop,ro ~/vsc_lab/extracted_shadows/vsc1 ~/vsc_lab/shadow_mounts/vsc1
fi
Subtask 3.2: Analyze Shadow Copy Contents
# Explore shadow copy file structure
find ~/vsc_lab/shadow_mounts/vsc1 -type f -name "*.txt" -o -name "*.doc" 2>/dev/null

# Create file listing with timestamps
find ~/vsc_lab/shadow_mounts/vsc1 -type f -exec ls -la {} \; > ~/vsc_lab/shadow_file_list.txt

# Search for specific file patterns
grep -r "important\|confidential\|sensitive" ~/vsc_lab/shadow_mounts/vsc1/ 2>/dev/null
Subtask 3.3: Recover Deleted Files
# Create recovery directory
mkdir -p ~/vsc_lab/recovered_files

# Copy files from shadow copies
if [ -d ~/vsc_lab/shadow_mounts/vsc1/Users ]; then
    cp -r ~/vsc_lab/shadow_mounts/vsc1/Users ~/vsc_lab/recovered_files/shadow1_users
fi

# Use fls from Sleuth Kit for detailed file analysis
fls -r ~/vsc_lab/windows_disk.img > ~/vsc_lab/file_system_analysis.txt

# Search for deleted files
grep "(deleted)" ~/vsc_lab/file_system_analysis.txt
Subtask 3.4: Compare Shadow Copy Versions
# Create comparison script
cat > ~/vsc_lab/compare_shadows.sh << 'EOF'
#!/bin/bash

echo "=== Shadow Copy Comparison Report ==="
echo "Generated: $(date)"
echo

# Compare file counts between shadow copies
if [ -d ~/vsc_lab/shadow_mounts/vsc1 ] && [ -d ~/vsc_lab/shadow_mounts/vsc2 ]; then
    echo "File count in VSC1: $(find ~/vsc_lab/shadow_mounts/vsc1 -type f | wc -l)"
    echo "File count in VSC2: $(find ~/vsc_lab/shadow_mounts/vsc2 -type f | wc -l)"
fi

# List unique files in each shadow copy
echo -e "\n=== Files unique to each shadow copy ==="
if [ -d ~/vsc_lab/shadow_mounts/vsc1 ]; then
    find ~/vsc_lab/shadow_mounts/vsc1 -type f > /tmp/vsc1_files.txt
fi
if [ -d ~/vsc_lab/shadow_mounts/vsc2 ]; then
    find ~/vsc_lab/shadow_mounts/vsc2 -type f > /tmp/vsc2_files.txt
fi

EOF

chmod +x ~/vsc_lab/compare_shadows.sh
./~/vsc_lab/compare_shadows.sh
Task 4: Timeline Analysis and Documentation
Subtask 4.1: Create Timeline from Shadow Copies
# Generate timeline using mactime
if command -v mactime &> /dev/null; then
    fls -m / -r ~/vsc_lab/windows_disk.img > ~/vsc_lab/bodyfile.txt
    mactime -b ~/vsc_lab/bodyfile.txt > ~/vsc_lab/timeline.txt
    head -20 ~/vsc_lab/timeline.txt
fi
Subtask 4.2: Generate Investigation Report
# Create comprehensive report
cat > ~/vsc_lab/vsc_investigation_report.txt << EOF
Volume Shadow Copy Investigation Report
======================================
Investigation Date: $(date)
Analyst: Lab Student
Image File: windows_disk.img

SUMMARY OF FINDINGS:
- Total shadow copies found: $(ls ~/vsc_lab/extracted_shadows/ 2>/dev/null | wc -l)
- Files recovered: $(find ~/vsc_lab/recovered_files -type f 2>/dev/null | wc -l)
- Analysis completed: $(date)

SHADOW COPY DETAILS:
$(cat ~/vsc_lab/shadow_analysis.txt 2>/dev/null | head -20)

RECOVERED FILES:
$(find ~/vsc_lab/recovered_files -type f -exec ls -la {} \; 2>/dev/null)

EOF

echo "Investigation report created: ~/vsc_lab/vsc_investigation_report.txt"
Subtask 4.3: Cleanup and Verification
# Verify all recovered data
echo "=== Lab Completion Verification ==="
echo "1. Shadow copies extracted: $(ls ~/vsc_lab/extracted_shadows/ 2>/dev/null | wc -l)"
echo "2. Files recovered: $(find ~/vsc_lab/recovered_files -type f 2>/dev/null | wc -l)"
echo "3. Report generated: $([ -f ~/vsc_lab/vsc_investigation_report.txt ] && echo "Yes" || echo "No")"

# Unmount all mounted filesystems
sudo umount ~/vsc_lab/shadow_mounts/vsc1 2>/dev/null
sudo umount ~/vsc_lab/shadow_mounts/vsc2 2>/dev/null
sudo umount ~/vsc_lab/vsc_mount 2>/dev/null

echo "Lab completed successfully!"
Troubleshooting Common Issues
Issue: vshadowinfo command not found Solution: Ensure libvshadow is properly installed and ldconfig was run

Issue: Permission denied when mounting Solution: Use sudo for mount operations and check file permissions

Issue: No shadow copies found Solution: Verify the disk image contains NTFS filesystem with VSC data

Conclusion
You have successfully completed Volume Shadow Copy extraction and analysis using open-source tools. This lab demonstrated how to:

Install and configure VShadow tools on Linux
Extract Volume Shadow Copies from Windows disk images
Mount and analyze shadow copy contents
Recover deleted files from historical snapshots
Generate forensic reports with timeline analysis
These skills are essential for digital forensics investigations, incident response, and data recovery scenarios. Volume Shadow Copies provide valuable historical data that can reveal file modifications, deletions, and system changes over time, making them crucial evidence sources in forensic examinations.
